          "body": "Numbers 25 opens with three verbs of descent compressed into two verses: the people 'began to play the harlot' (25:1), they were 'invited' to sacrificial meals (25:2), and they 'ate and bowed down' (25:2). Idolatry in this chapter does not begin with theological argument or forced conversion; it begins with sexual attraction and a dinner invitation. The daughters of Moab do not ask Israel to renounce YHWH — they ask Israel to come eat. Physical appetite opens the door to religious capitulation. Verse 3 names the destination: 'Israel joined themselves to Baal of Peor' — the verb *tsamad* suggesting not a casual visit but a yoke-bond, a committed attachment. This is the pattern Hosea will later anatomize (Hosea 9:10), Paul will warn against in 1 Corinthians 10:8 (citing this very episode), and that Revelation 2:14 will identify as the teaching of Balaam: use feasting and sexual immorality as the weapons of spiritual warfare that cannot succeed by frontal assault."
